  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=54043
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | last = Smith
  | first = David
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Delayed Into 2004
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = December, 2003
  | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_zd1up/is_200312/ai_ziff113779
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The demo disc of ''Ninja Gaiden'' came with the March 2004 edition of [[Famitsu|Famitsu Xbox]],<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Anoop Gantayat
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Demo Busted
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2004-02-13]]
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/492/492400p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Demo Disc
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2004-01-20]]
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/473/473498p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> on [[12 February]] [[2004]]. In the demo, the player is restricted to the ninja fortress in the retail version's chapter one. However, Ryu starts off with three fully upgraded melee weapons, two types of shurikens, and a bow. He is also equipped with the Art of Inazuma ninpo, which shoots out bolts of lightning. This gives the player a taste of the later features in the retail version. The demo offers only the Normal and Hard difficulty levels to choose from.

''Ninja Gaiden''<nowiki>'s</nowiki> American retail release was two weeks earlier than its Japanese release,<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Smith
  | first = David
  | title = Final Ninja Gaiden Release Date
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = February, 2004
  | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_zd1up/is_200402/ai_ziff120076
