Work continued on the project despite the retail release, and downloadable contents in the form of ''Hurricane Pack''s were announced to be available for download via [[Xbox Live]] from August 2004.<ref>{{cite news
  | coauthors = SPOnG Staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden expansion pack now available for download
  | publisher = SPOnG
  | date = [[2004-08-11]]
  | url = http://news.spong.com/article/7389
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The ''Pack''s are part of the qualifying process for the Master Ninja Tournament World Wide Finals.

'''''Hurricane Pack 1''''' was available for download since [[August 9]], [[2004]]. It reused ''Ninja Gaiden'''s Story Mode, but added several new foes like the blue furred humanoid [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Cat Fiends]], the [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Dino Fiends]] wearing [[triceratops]] skull masks, and upgraded versions of the Vigoor military forces. Modifications were made to the scoring system to reward clearing only encounters for the first time, and for fast kills. The player is now able to manually rotate the camera, and an Intercept technique (similar to [[Soul Calibur II]]'s Guard Impact),<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Intercept
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2004-07-28]]
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/534/534280p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> was introduced.

'''''Hurricane Pack 2''''' was available for download since [[September 27]], [[2004]]. It integrated all the features of ''Hurricane Pack 1'', but changed the story and game world. With the aid of a new weapon, the Lunar, the player has to fight through several rounds of combats to rescue Rachel from the twin Ancient Fiends, [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Nicchae]] and [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Ishtaros]]. Going up through the palace, and into the nether world, the player can only shop and save after certain rounds of combats with old foes and a few new foes, like the slide tackling [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Crow Shadows]] and the great sword wielding [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Nightmare Fiends]]. 

==Master Ninja Tournaments==
The original purpose of the first ''Hurricane Pack'' was for the Master Ninja World Tournament qualification, and the second pack was a separate tournament on its own. With the events' conclusions, the packs' ranking boards are left up online for players to continue competing their scores. Tecmo's planned to hold a Master Ninja Tournament for all ''Ninja Gaiden'' players to participate in. Making use of the online ranking capability of the game, three rounds of competition plus regional playoffs were held to select the finalists who would proceed to the Master Tournament World Championship. Their flight and accommodation were paid for by the organizers.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Smith
  | first = David
  | title = Tecmo Announces Master Ninja Tournament
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = March, 2004
  | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_zd1up/is_200403/ai_ziff120584
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Registration for the competition started on [[May 3]], [[2004]].<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Fudge
  | first = James
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Soon (Xbox)
  | publisher = [[GameSpy]]
  | date = [[2004-04-15]]
  | url = http://xbox.gamespy.com/xbox/ninja-gaiden/506899p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = SPOnG staff
  | title = Supreme Master Ninja Overlord's free trip to Tokyo!
  | publisher = SPOnG
  | date = [[2004-07-27]]
  | url = http://news.spong.com/article/7219
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

'''Master Ninja Tournament 1''', the first round of competition was decided by players playing ''Ninja Gaiden''<nowiki>'s</nowiki> Story Mode on Normal difficulty, and submitting their scores to the online scoreboard. It was limited to [[North America]]n and [[Canada|Canadian]] players. It began on [[May 12]], [[2004]]. The participation rate was immense, and was reported to be the highest participated tournament on [[Xbox Live]] then.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = GamePro staff
  | title = Tecmo Adds New Downloadable Content for Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[GamePro]]
  | date = [[2004-06-24]]
  | url = http://www.gamepro.com/news.cfm?article_id=36386
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The deadline for score submission was [[June 4]], [[2004]]. Prizes were t-shirts and wristbands.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = z36
  | title = Ninja Gaiden - Master Ninja Tournament for Xbox Live
  | publisher = DreamStation.cc
  | date = [[2004-05-30]]
  | url = http://www.dreamstation.cc/news/video_games/id4009
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

Controversy however surrounded the first round.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Xbox-HQ staff
  | title = Master Ninja Tourney : 1st Round Controversy
  | publisher = Xbox-HQ.com
  | date = [[2004-08-01]]
  | url = http://www.xbox-hq.com/html/modules.php?name=News&file=print&sid=1080
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The official rules were only posted 10 days before the end of the first round, and the initial conception of there being 100 qualifiers for the next round was revealed to be mistaken - only the top three would receive a [[bokken]] signed by Tomonobu Itagaki, and the chance to proceed to the championship.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Goldstein
  | first = Hilary
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Heats Up
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2004-05-26]]
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/519/519150p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The first placed player, Ryan Martoni aka 'taibhse' obtained a score which many players declared as unattainable by fair means. Even Martoni himself was uncertain how he got his score.

[[Image:MNT Welcome Party Maruyo.jpg|thumb|200px|left|'maruyo' trying out the game for the finals at the welcome party.]]'''Master Ninja Tournament 2''' was the second round of the competition. Participating players had to register by [[August 2]], [[2004]] (later extended to [[August 9]], [[2004]]),<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Coleman
  | first = Stephen
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Registration Extended
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2004-08-03]]
  | url = http://games.ign.com/articles/535/535413p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> download ''Hurricane Pack 1'', complete it, and submit their scores by [[August 22]], [[2004]] for the North American and [[Japan]]ese regions; [[September 2]], [[2004]] for the [[Europe]]an region. The European region participants got to win the same prizes as the North American region had in Master Ninja Tournament 1,<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Berardini
  | first = César
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament for Europe Announced
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = [[2004-07-26]]
  | url = http://news.teamxbox.com/xbox/6375/Master-Ninja-Tournament-for-Europe-Announced/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> however only the top European champion could proceed to the championship. The European champion turned out to be Darren Forman aka 'Kayin Amoh'.

[[Image:MNT Game On.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The Ninja Gaiden Master Tournament World Championship proceeding on.]]Of the three Master Ninja Tournament 1 winners, only one of them would make it to the championship by beating out the other two in this round. Derek Ian Edwin Kisman aka 'SnapDragon', easily trounced the other two, and earned his spot. The highest Master Ninja Tournament 2 score for the North American region also qualified for the finals. There was controversy as the top North American player nicknamed 'Saryah' was disqualified for failing to declare his age in his gamer profile, and David Barlog aka 'Captain Tuttle' the second highest scorer was passed over for being unable to present his passport on time. The spot finally went to Grant Goodwin aka 'Grantisimo', who squeezed in as the third highest scoring North American just before the deadline as stated in the rules.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Berardini
  | first = César
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Finals Details
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = [[2004-09-15]]
  | url = http://news.teamxbox.com/xbox/6768/Master-Ninja-Tournament-Finals-Details/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The top two Japanese scorers, 'maruyo' and 'panzerorta40148' rounded off the finalists to the championship.

Like the first round, the second round of the competition broke the record for online participation of a tournament on Xbox Live.<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Breaks Records Again with Highest Registration Numbers
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = [[2004-09-03]]
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/news.html?sid=6106689
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

The '''Ninja Gaiden Master Tournament World Championship''' was held at the [[Tokyo Game Show]] 2004 on September 25. The five finalists played simultaneously an extracted version of ''Hurricane Pack 2'', on raised walkways while commentators called out the action. The winner was judged by the highest score, and Yasunori Otsuka aka 'panzerorta40148' outscored the rest to take the championship. He was presented a plaque by Tomonobu Itagaki himself.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Carle
  | first = Chris
  | title = TGS 2004: Ninja Gaiden Master Tournament World Championship
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2004-09-25]]
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/551/551186p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = GMR Magazine staff
  | title = Tokyo Game Show 2004: Master Ninja Tourny Concludes
  | publisher = [[GMR (magazine)|GMR Magazine]]
  | date = December, 2004
  | url = http://www.xbox-hq.com/html/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=1316
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

'''Master Ninja Tournament 3''' was a comparatively low key affair started on [[September 27]], [[2004]].<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Tecmo Announces Third and Final Master Ninja Tournament, Hurricane Pack: Volume II
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = [[2004-09-24]]
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/news.html?sid=6108698
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The players had to download ''Hurricane Pack 2'' and submit their scores by [[October 22]], [[2004]]. Only the top scorer would be declared the winner and be awarded with a plethora of prizes including a copy of ''Ninja Gaiden'' signed by Tomonobu Itagaki and a copy of ''[[Dead or Alive Ultimate]]''. The top scoring 100 players received ''Ninja Gaiden'' boxers or wristbands. 50 pairs of Ninja "Dog" boxers were awarded to random participants.
<br style="clear:both;"/>

==Versions and Expansions==
===''Ninja Gaiden Black''===
{{Infobox CVG
|title = Ninja Gaiden Black
|image = [[Image:Ngbcover.jpg|256px|''Ninja Gaiden Black'' North American box cover]]
|developer = [[Team Ninja]]
|publisher = [[Tecmo]]
|designer = [[Tomonobu Itagaki]]
|released = {{flagicon|USA}} [[September 20]], [[2005]]<br />
{{flagicon|Japan}} [[September 29]], [[2005]]<br />
{{flagicon|EU}} [[October 21]], [[2005]]<br />
|genre = [[Action-Adventure]]
|modes = [[Single player]]
|ratings = [[Entertainment Software Rating Board|ESRB]]: M (Mature) <br /> [[Pan European Game Information|PEGI]]: 18+ <br />[[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]]: 15<br />[[Unterhaltungssoftware Selbstkontrolle|USK]]: 18+ <br />
|platforms = [[Xbox]]
|picture format = [[480i]] [[SDTV]]<br />
[[480p]] [[EDTV]]<br />[[720p]] [[HDTV]] (Xbox 360 only)
|media = [[DVD-ROM]]
|input = Standard Xbox Controller
}}

After the releases of the ''Hurricane Packs'', [[Team Ninja]] was rumored to be working on ''[[Ninja Gaiden II (Xbox 360)|Ninja Gaiden II]]'', and would announce it in May's [[E3 Media and Business Summit|E3]] 2005 for release on the upcoming [[Xbox 360]]. However [[Tecmo]] announced the project to be '''''Ninja Gaiden Black''''' for the [[Xbox]].<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Gibson
  | first = Ellie
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: BLACK info
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = [[2005-05-23]]
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=59375
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The game was shortly listed as playable for the [[Tokyo Game Show]] 2005,<ref>{{cite news
  | author = SPOnG staff
  | title = Tokyo Game Show - Complete Essential Game List
  | publisher = SPOnG
  | date = [[2005-09-14]]
  | url = http://news.spong.com/article/9132/Tokyo+Game+Show+%96+Complete+Essential+Game+List?cb=403
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> and was released on schedule in September 2005 with loads of content for a comparatively low price.<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black Ships to Retailers
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = [[2005-09-21]]
  | url = http://64.78.9.175/press.asp?id=20
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref> Those who pre-ordered the game received a free exclusive t-shirt as well.<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Tecmo Announces Free Retro T-Shirt As Ninja Gaiden Black Pre-Order Incentive
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = [[2005-09-01]]
  | url = http://64.78.9.175/press.asp?id=18
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref>

Considered to be the complete ''Ninja Gaiden'' experience by the designer [[Tomonobu Itagaki]] himself,<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Cory J. Herndon
  | title = Dev Interview: Tecmo w/Itagaki-san
  | publisher = Xbox.com
  | date = [[2005-05-23]]
  | url = http://www.xbox.com/en-US/games/d/deadoralive4/20050523-tecmo.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}
</ref> ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' integrated all of the new features in the two ''Hurricane Packs'', along with new features of its own, such as the all new Mission Mode, and the new easy difficulty - Ninja Dog. According to interviews with Itagaki, the Ninja Dog difficulty was added only grudgingly.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Mielke
  | first = James
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black from 1UP.com
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = [[2005-05-13]]
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=0&cId=3140456
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> He felt the standard difficulty implemented in the game was reasonable for any casual player if they persevered through the difficult parts.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = 1UP.com staff
  | title = Previews: Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = [[2004-09-05]]
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3061511
  | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}
</ref> However, due to the strong outcries to the game's difficulty, he instituted the Ninja Dog mode as a double-edged compromise: it can only be accessed through dying three successive times (similar to the Special Edition of ''[[Devil May Cry 3: Dante's Awakening#Devil May Cry 3: Special Edition|Devil May Cry 3]]'') within the first stage, at which point the player is asked, "Do you wish to abandon the way of the ninja?" If the player accepts, the game enters Ninja Dog and continues on under a condescending atmosphere - pink ribbons for accessories, Ayane taking on an attitude to Ryu, etc.

''Ninja Gaiden Black'' is, however, more difficult than the original release, especially on the higher difficulties. Several bosses including [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Leaders of the Fiends|Spirit Doku]] and the Dark Disciple attack faster and more furiously, plus a variety of dangerous new foes have been added to make life even harder. Furthermore, players who have previously played ''Ninja Gaiden'' will find the Flying Swallow move, previously a powerful and useful technique, has been noticeably toned down and is a mere shadow of its old self, with a couple of new enemies having moves specifically to punish usage of it against them. On Hard difficulty and above, foes block the Flying Swallow more frequently, forcing players to adapt to a new style of fighting.

[[Image:NGB FS Counter.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Ryu's Flying Swallow meets a bayonet in his gut.]]''Hurricane Pack 1'''s design, along with several new in-game cutscenes were effectively integrated into Story Mode, and playable on all difficulty levels, including the new Ninja Dog and Master Ninja difficulty. Encounters were added on higher levels of difficulty to surprise players on their first play, and almost all foes were given grabbing, guard breaking or crushing attacks. This coupled with the increase in the enemies' aggressiveness made the player more wary on their toes, and less likely to '[[Turtle (game term)|turtle]]' in ''Ninja Gaiden Black''.

New elements are continually introduced as the player clears the higher difficulties with the aid of the Lunar and Smoke Bombs (a new projectile which aids in distracting enemies). As the player attempts the higher difficulties, he will encounter foes from the ''Hurricane Packs'', as well as new ones, like explosive bats, flame ninjas (red-clad ninjas whose attacks inflict additional flame damage), and Ryu's evil shadows, the [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Doppelganger Fiends]]. New costumes for Ryu were also available for the player to unlock, as well as the ''[[Ninja Gaiden (arcade game)|Ninja Gaiden arcade game]]'' (which took the place of the three bonus unlockable NES games in ''Ninja Gaiden'').

Mission Mode introduced 46 missions concentrating on combat in small arenas. The majority of the missions are new scenarios, while several are modified versions of fights found in Story Mode. The game the finalists played in the World Wide Master Ninja Tournament 2004 finalists was implemented as one of the missions. The longest mission is Eternal Legend, which is ''Hurricane Pack 2'' implemented on ''Ninja Gaiden Black''<nowiki>'s</nowiki> engine.
<br style="clear:both;"/>

===''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''===
{{Infobox CVG| title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma
|image = [[Image:Ninja Gaiden Sigma BoxCover.jpg|256px|"Ninja Gaiden Sigma" PlayStation 3 cover art.]]
|developer = [[Team Ninja]]
|publisher = [[Tecmo]]
|publisher = [[Tecmo]]<br /> {{flagicon|Europe}} [[Eidos Interactive]]
|designer = [[Yousuke Hayashi]]
|release = {{vgrelease|Japan|JP|[[June 14]], [[2007]]}}<br />{{vgrelease|North America|NA|[[July 3]], [[2007]]}}<br />{{vgrelease|Europe|EU|[[July 6]], [[2007]]}}<br />{{vgrelease|Australia|AU|[[July 13]], [[2007]]}}
|genre = [[Action-adventure game]]
|modes = [[Single player]]
|ratings = [[Entertainment Software Ratings Board|ESRB]]: M (Mature)<br />[[Office of Film and Literature Classification (Australia)|OFLC]]: MA15+<br />[[British Board of Film Classification|BBFC]]: 15<br />[[Computer Entertainment Rating Organization|CERO]]: D
|platforms = [[PlayStation 3]]
|media = [[Blu-ray Disc]]
|requirements =
|input = [[Sixaxis]]
|picture format = [[720p]], [[1080i]], [[1080p]] (HDTV)<br />[[480p]] (EDTV)<br />[[480i]] (SDTV)
}}

Tecmo announced in the September 2006 issue of [[Famitsu]] the next project in the ''Ninja Gaiden'' series would be [[Video game remake|remaking]] ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' into '''''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''''' for the [[PlayStation 3]].<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Robinson
  | first = Andy
  | title = Ninja Gaiden pulls a flying kick on PS3
  | publisher = [[Computer and Video Games (magazine)|Computer and Video Games]]
  | date = [[2006-09-20]]
  | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=146205
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = SPOnG staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Heads to PS3
  | publisher = SPOnG
  | date = [[2006-09-20]]
  | url = http://news.spong.com/article/10806
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> This was officially announced by [[Sony]] at the [[Tokyo Game Show]] 2006.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = SPOnG staff
  | title = TGS: Sony Announces Five New PS3 Titles
  | publisher = SPOnG
  | date = [[2006-09-22]]
  | url = http://news.spong.com/article/10821
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> [[Yousuke Hayashi]] was appointed the [[game director]] of this remake, and [[Eidos]] managed to purchase the publishing rights for Europe and North America.

[[Tomonobu Itagaki]] while having no direct involvement in the project, had stated ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' is only for PlayStation owners who never got the chance to experience what ''Ninja Gaiden'' and ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' had to offer, which is why this version will remain exclusively for the PS3.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Gantayat
  | first = Anoop
  | title = No Sigma For 360
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2007-06-01]]
  | url = http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/793/793679p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

[[GameStop]] announced in April 2007 that it would be releasing limited number of copies of ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma Collectors Edition'' for the North American market.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Mcwhertor
  | first = Michael
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Gets Collectors Edition
  | publisher = [[Kotaku]]
  | date = [[2007-04-23]]
  | url = http://kotaku.com/gaming/ninja-gaiden-sigma/ninja-gaiden-sigma-gets-collectors-edition-254679.php
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> They were sold at ten US dollars more than the standard edition, with the only extra exclusive content being a 'behind-the-scenes' DVD of Team Ninja, as the advertised exclusive code was applicable for the standard editions as well. Hopes for a ''Collectors Edition'' for Europe were dashed with a followup announcement by Eidos.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Plunkett
  | first = Luke
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma CE European Details...Announced
  | publisher = [[Kotaku]]
  | date = [[2007-04-25]]
  | url = http://kotaku.com/gaming/ninja-gaiden-sigma/ninja-gaiden-sigma-ce-european-detailsannounced-255068.php
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | last = Purchese
  | first = Rob
  | title = Sigma Special Edition iffy for Europe
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = [[2007-04-24]]
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=75667
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

The [[Japan]]-based singer, [[Leah Dizon]] was contracted to be the [[celebrity]] promoter for the game, starring in and singing the song for its commercial.<ref>{{cite video
  | year = 2007
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Japan TV Commercial
  | url = http://www.gametrailers.com/player/usermovies/69850.html
  | format = flv
  | medium = Television commercial
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]] Ltd
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Her autographed posters were also prizes for the game's Japanese launch.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Ashcroft
  | first = Brian
  | title = Win Signed Ninja Gaiden Sigma Poster
  | publisher = [[Kotaku]]
  | date = [[2007-06-12]]
  | url = http://kotaku.com/gaming/not-a-real-ninja/win-signed-ninja-gaiden-sigma-poster-267988.php
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Limited supplies of free t-shirts were given to those who pre-ordered the game for the North American launch.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = William Haley
  | title = Free Stuff for the Week of 5/26/07
  | publisher = Destructoid
  | date = [[2007-06-12]]
  | url = http://www.destructoid.com/free-stuff-for-the-week-of-5-26-07-31755.phtml
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

Contrary to claims of this being the "more complete" version,<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Wyman
  | first = Walt
  | title = TGS 06: PS3 Ninja Gaiden Detailed
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = [[2007-09-22]]
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6158343.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>
{{cite news
  | last = de Vries
  | first = Nino
  | title = Ninja Gaiden PS3 Bound
  | publisher = Playstatic
  | date = [[2007-09-22]]
  | url = http://www.playstatic.com/news/4
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | last = Burman
  | first = Rob
  | title = Eidos Unleashing Ninjas in Europe
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2007-04-20]]
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/782/782234p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> almost all of the bonus features from the two previous versions were excluded from this version. Unlockable costumes were reduced to only two, and the old NES and arcade games which can be unlocked previously were eliminated. The introductory movie chronicling the legend of the Dark Dragon Blade and the Dragon Sword was also no longer in the game.

Graphics were overhauled to [[High-definition video|high definition]] standards. Vast changes were made to the layout of a few environments. A great number of new save and shop locations were added, and Rachel's three chapters were simply inserted amongst Ryu's Story Mode chapters. New foes, like the biker [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Vigoor military|MVAPs]], the fish-men [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|girtablilu]], and the wisp-like [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|phantoms]], were introduced with the two new bosses, [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Vigoor military|Gamov]] and [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Vigoor military|Alternator]], with quite a few changes made to the specifications (AI, damage, etc) of the old foes. The player can fight these foes with the new weapon, a pair of [[katana]]s, the Dragon's Claw & Tiger's Fang.

Ryu's reverse wind technique was replaced with that of his ninja foes. He can now fight on water, and shoot arrows in mid-air. The most prominent change allowed the player to use restoration items without going through the menus. The controller can also be shaken to increase a casted ninpo's power.

From [[August 30]], [[2007]] onwards, Survival Mode is available in the form of three separate packages for ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' on the [[PlayStation Network]], each costing a small fee to download.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Gantayat
  | first = Anoop
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Downloadable Content Announced
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2007-08-03]]
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/810/810350p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Each package adds a set of themed missions (Weapon Master, Speed Master, Rachel Master) to the new Survival Mode option.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Chris Roper
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Expansion Pack Hands-on
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = [[2007-09-06]]
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/818/818522p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-06 }}
</ref> The player goes through the missions without any restoration item, and keeps fighting enemies until the character's life is reduced to zero. Online rankings primarily keep track of the player's individual mission records, in terms of the number of kills.

A demo was released on [[April 26]], [[2007]], over the PlayStation Network. Like the original ''Ninja Gaiden''<nowiki>'s</nowiki> demo, the player is restricted to chapter one's game world. However the demo unlocks the next higher difficulty when the player completes it on a lower difficulty. The player can also play as Rachel in a separate mission.

On starting the very first game on the retail version, the player can be rewarded with a bonus amount of yellow essence based on the player's achievements in the demo. The demo exhibited a scoring glitch which resulted in ridiculously high scores on the leaderboards to the dismay of many ''Ninja Gaiden'' veterans.
<br style="clear:both;"/>

==Regional censorship==
<div style="font-size: 90%;float:right;border-left:1em solid white">
{| class="wikitable"
|+ Human Decapitation Featured
! &nbsp; !! NTSC/J !! NTSC/U !! PAL
|-
! ''Ninja Gaiden''
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#FF90A8" | No
|-
! ''Ninja Gaiden Black''
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|-
! ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''
|align="center" bgcolor="#FF90A8" | No
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#FF90A8" | No
|}
</div>

Being rated as a 'Mature' video game, ''Ninja Gaiden'' can retain its heavy gore content (blood, violence, decapitations, grotesque monsters) without any censorship. However, the ratings systems for certain countries prohibit beheadings from being depicted in them. Several of these decisions were based on public opinion over current events, and as such there are differences in the rulings between versions.

Despite heavy suspicions that the European release of the game would be censored in certain aspects, [[Microsoft]] reassured the crowd in March 2004 that the gore would be left intact.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Bramwell
  | first = Tom
  | title = Ninja Gaiden has NOT been censored for Europe
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = [[2004-03-12]]
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=54864
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = SPOnG staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden censored in Europe
  | publisher = SPOnG
  | date = [[2004-03-08]]
  | url = http://news.spong.com/article/6289
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> A month later, however they admitted the European PAL version would exclude decapitation of human foes.<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Bramwell
  | first = Tom
  | title = Ninja Gaiden stripped of decapitations
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = [[2004-04-21]]
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=55274
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | last = Fahey
  | first = Rob
  | title = Confirmed: Ninja Gaiden censored for European release
  | publisher = [[GamesIndustry.biz]]
  | date = [[2004-04-21]]
  | url = http://www.gamesindustry.biz/content_page.php?section_name=pub&aid=3328
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = SPOnG staff
  | title = Tecmo Gaiden head-loss confirmed
  | publisher = SPOnG
  | date = [[2004-04-22]]
  | url = http://psp.spong.com/article/6532?cb=157
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> While the submitted material was uncensored,<ref>{{cite news
  | author = SPOnG staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Content Cuts - The Truth Revealed
  | publisher = SPOnG
  | date = [[2004-03-12]]
  | url = http://news.spong.com/article/6324
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> [[Germany|German]] law forbids games featuring the decapitations portrayed in ''Ninja Gaiden'', to be released to those 18 years old and above. As such, decapitations were removed from the PAL retail versions. However, a year later, ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' was accredited with the same rating by the [[Unterhaltungssoftware Selbstkontrolle|USK]], but the decapitations were left untouched in the [[PAL region|PAL]] versions.

Since 2006, [[Japan]] has become more stringent with [[Computer Entertainment Rating Organization|CERO]], its violence rating system. Therefore, ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' cannot feature human decapitation unless Tecmo is willing to accept a 'Z' rating for the game. As it is sold in Japan under the 'D' rating, there are no decapitations in the [[NTSC|NTSC/J]] version of ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''.

==Reception==
<div style="font-size: 90%;float:right;border-left:1em solid white">
{| class="wikitable"
